sentences: Ernest Fanelli (29 June 1860 – 24 November 1917) was a French composer of Italian descent who is best known for sparking a controversy about the origins of Impressionist music when his composition Tableaux symphoniques was first performed in 1912.
He studied music at the Conservatoire de Paris for a few years from 1876, but was expelled because of his disputes with the teaching staff.

The claim that he studied there with Charles-Valentin Alkan is mistaken, as Alkan quit the Conservatoire in 1848, but he may have studied with Alkan's brother, Napoléon, who was the Conservatoire professor of solfège at the time.
In 1912, Fanelli was seeking work as a musical copyist, and submitted a manuscript to Gabriel Pierné as an example of his neat handwriting.
He had given up composing in 1894, several years before he became well known, and could not or would not resume creative work.
The second part, Fête dans le palais du Pharaon, depicting royal festivities, was never published, but was performed in 1913.
Les Deux tonneaux (1879), three acts, after Voltaire.

symphonic poem Thèbes (1883)

Une Nuit chez Sophor (1891)
Humoresques (1892–1894)
string quintet, "L'Aneau" (1894)
Pierné was intrigued by the music itself, which Fanelli told him was one of his own compositions, Tableaux symphoniques, written nearly 30 years earlier.
